.TH NLEASH 1 "January 2026" "nleash" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
nleash \- limit outbound bandwidth for a process using cgroup v2 and tc
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B nleash
--pid PID --rate RATE [--iface IFACE]

.B nleash
--rate RATE [--iface IFACE] -- command [args...]

.B nleash
--pid PID --clear

.B nleash
--list [--json]
.SH DESCRIPTION
nleash applies egress bandwidth limits to a process using cgroup v2 and tc (HTB + cls_cgroup).
It creates a child cgroup under the target's existing cgroup and classifies traffic by cgroup.id.

Ingress shaping is intentionally not supported in v1.
.PP
For non-root usage, nleash can exec a setuid-root helper (nleash-helper) that performs
the privileged operations. The helper enforces that non-root callers can only
act on their own processes and drops privileges before executing commands.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR --pid " " PID
Target an existing process ID.
.TP
.BR --rate " " RATE
Bandwidth rate string accepted by tc (e.g., 500kbit, 10mbit, 1gbit).
.TP
.BR --iface " " IFACE
Network interface to shape. If omitted, the default route interface is detected via ip route.
.TP
.B --clear
Clear the leash for the given PID (with safety identity checks).
.TP
.B --list
List current leashes (from /run/nleash/state.txt). Output includes UID.
.TP
.B --json
Output machine-readable JSON for --list.
.SH REQUIREMENTS
- Linux with cgroup v2 mounted at /sys/fs/cgroup
- Kernel support for cls_cgroup and cgroup.id
- CAP_NET_ADMIN and cgroup write permissions (run as root)
- Userspace tools: tc, ip, modprobe
.SH SAFETY
Leashes are keyed by (pid, starttime_ticks, boot_id). If the identity does not match during
--clear, nleash does not touch any live process and only removes stale tc/cgroup state.
.SH FILES
/run/nleash/state.txt
/run/nleash/nextid
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR tc (8),
.BR ip (8)
